```java
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class MyClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try (FileReader fr = new FileReader("input.txt")) {
            Scanner scanner = new Scanner(fr);
            while (scanner.hasNextLine()) {
                String line = scanner.nextLine();
                // Do something with the input
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.err.println("Error reading file.");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `FileReader` object is closed inside the try-with-resources statement, which is good practice. However, the `Scanner` object is not closed, and it will remain open until the garbage collector runs. This could cause memory leaks or other problems if the `Scanner` object references large amounts of data.

